Online Supplement S4

Detailed Output for Kuskokwim River Chinook Salmon SSM-vM

Staton et al.

Model Description

Model Identifier: SSM-vM

Recruitment Process Error Variance: Shared recruitment variance and covariance among all populations and population pairs.

Maturity Schedule: Time-varying, but shared completely among populations.

All other model components are the same as the other state-space models.

Spawner-Recruit Relationships

Blue points are “fully-observed” spawner recruit pairs, i.e., all age-specific escapements were observed for that brood year, as well as the escapement that produced those pairs were observed.

Black points are posterior medians of the latent state pairs – only those brood years with a matching spawner abundance were used (i.e., the first 7 brood years are excluded).

Fit to Data

In all figures, blue points are observed data, black lines are posterior medians, and grey regions are 95% equal-tailed credible intervals.

Recruitment

NOTE: The state-space model does not fit to recruitment. It reconstructs recruitment internally by fitting true latent states in the calendar years to observed states of escapement by population, aggregate harvest, and age composition if available. This plot is included only illustrate how well the model’s reconstructions match one rational way of doing it external to the model.

Mixed-Stock Reference Points

In the table below:

  • \(S^*_p\) is the minimum escapement of the mixed-stock that is expected to have no more than \(p \cdot 100\)% of the populations overfished
  • \(U^*_p\) is the maximum exploitation rate of the mixed-stock that is expected to have no more than \(p \cdot 100\)% of the populations overfished
  • \(S_{\text{MSY}}\) and \(U_{\text{MSY}}\) are the mixed stock escapement and exploitation rate, respectively, expected to produce maximum sustained yield.

These reference points are for only the 13 populations included in the analysis, not all populations in the Kuskokwim River.

JAGS Model

Code

model
{
    log_resid_0a <- 0
    phi ~ dunif(-0.99, 0.99)
    for (s in 1:ns) {
        U_msy[s] ~ dunif(0.01, 0.99)
        log_S_msy[s] ~ dnorm(0, 0.001)  I(1, 11.5)
        S_msy[s] <- exp(log_S_msy[s])
        alpha[s] <- exp(U_msy[s])/(1 - U_msy[s])
        log_alpha[s] <- log(alpha[s])
        beta[s] <- U_msy[s]/S_msy[s]
        log_resid_0[s] <- log_resid_0a
    }
    sig.common ~ dunif(0, 2)
    var.common <- sig.common^2
    rho.common ~ dunif(-0.05, 1)
    rho.vec[1] <- 1
    rho.vec[2] <- rho.common
    for (i in 1:vcov_N) {
        rho_mat[vcov_row[i], vcov_col[i]] <- rho.vec[vcov_ind[i]]
        Sigma_R[vcov_row[i], vcov_col[i]] <- var.common * rho.vec[vcov_ind[i]]
    }
    Tau_R[1:ns, 1:ns] <- inverse(Sigma_R[1:ns, 1:ns])
    for (s in 1:ns) {
        sigma_R[s] <- sqrt(Sigma_R[s, s])
    }
    for (s in 1:ns) {
        R_eq[s] <- log_alpha[s]/beta[s]
        R0[s] <- R_eq[s]
        log_R0[s] <- log(R0[s])
        log_R_mean1[1, s] <- log_R0[s]
        R_mean1[1, s] <- R0[s]
        log_R_mean2[1, s] <- log_R_mean1[1, s] + phi * log_resid_0[s]
        for (y in 2:a_max) {
            R_mean1[y, s] <- R0[s]
            log_R_mean1[y, s] <- log_R0[s]
            log_R_mean2[y, s] <- log_R_mean1[y, s] + phi * log_resid[y - 
                1, s]
        }
        for (y in (a_max + 1):ny) {
            R_mean1[y, s] <- S[y - a_max, s] * exp(log_alpha[s] - 
                beta[s] * S[y - a_max, s])
            log_R_mean1[y, s] <- log(R_mean1[y, s])
            log_R_mean2[y, s] <- log_R_mean1[y, s] + phi * log_resid[y - 
                1, s]
        }
    }
    for (y in 1:ny) {
        log_R[y, 1:ns] ~ dmnorm(log_R_mean2[y, 1:ns], Tau_R[1:ns, 
            1:ns])
    }
    for (y in 1:ny) {
        for (s in 1:ns) {
            R[y, s] <- exp(log_R[y, s])
            log_resid[y, s] <- log_R[y, s] - log_R_mean1[y, s]
        }
    }
    prob[1] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
    prob[2] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
    prob[3] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
    pi[1] <- prob[1]
    pi[2] <- prob[2] * (1 - pi[1])
    pi[3] <- prob[3] * (1 - pi[1] - pi[2])
    pi[4] <- 1 - pi[1] - pi[2] - pi[3]
    D_scale ~ dunif(0.03, 1)
    D_sum <- 1/D_scale^2
    for (a in 1:na) {
        dir_alpha[a] <- D_sum * pi[a]
        for (y in 1:ny) {
            g[y, a] ~ dgamma(dir_alpha[a], 1)
            p[y, a] <- g[y, a]/sum(g[y, 1:na])
        }
    }
    for (s in 1:ns) {
        for (t in 1:nt) {
            for (a in 1:na) {
                N_tas[t, a, s] <- R[t + na - a, s] * p[t + na - 
                  a, a]
            }
            N[t, s] <- sum(N_tas[t, 1:na, s])
            S[t, s] <- N[t, s] * (1 - U[t] * v[s])
            C[t, s] <- N[t, s] * (U[t] * v[s])
        }
    }
    for (t in 1:nt) {
        U[t] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
        C_tot[t] <- sum(C[t, 1:ns])
    }
    for (i in 1:n_age_stocks) {
        for (t in 1:nt) {
            for (a in 1:na) {
                q[t, a, i] <- N_tas[t, a, age_stocks[i]]/N[t, 
                  age_stocks[i]]
            }
        }
    }
    for (t in 1:nt) {
        log_C_tot[t] <- log(C_tot[t])
        C_tot_t_obs[t] ~ dlnorm(log_C_tot[t], tau_C_obs[t])
    }
    for (i in 1:S_obs_n) {
        log_S[i] <- log(S[S_obs_t[i], S_obs_s[i]])
        S_obs[i] ~ dlnorm(log_S[i], tau_S_obs[i])
    }
    for (i in 1:n_age_stocks) {
        for (t in 1:nt) {
            x_tas_obs[t, 1:na, i] ~ dmulti(q[t, 1:na, i], ESS_ts[t, 
                i])
        }
    }
}
